","marks":1,"options":["46,XY karyotype with ambiguous genitalia","46,XX karyotype with virilisation","Complete absence of external genitalia","Normal male development until puberty","Excessive androgenisation at birth"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E5-alpha reductase deficiency is characterised by a \u003Cstrong\u003E46,XY karyotype with ambiguous genitalia\u003C/strong\u003E. The enzyme deficiency prevents adequate conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone during foetal development, leading to incomplete masculinisation of external genitalia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E46,XX karyotype with virilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - This condition only affects genetic males (46,XY)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete absence of external genitalia\u003C/strong\u003E - External genitalia are present but ambiguous\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal male development until puberty\u003C/strong\u003E - Abnormalities are present from birth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive androgenisation at birth\u003C/strong\u003E - There is insufficient androgenisation due to lack of dihydrotestosterone\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring puberty, rising testosterone levels may cause partial virilisation despite the enzyme deficiency, as testosterone itself has some androgenic effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["5-alpha reductase converts testosterone to dihydrotestosterone, which is essential for male external genital development during foetal life","5-alpha reductase deficiency presents with ambiguous genitalia in genetic males (46,XY) due to insufficient dihydrotestosterone","At puberty, rising testosterone levels can cause partial virilisation despite the enzyme deficiency"],"references":["Odame I, Donaldson MD, Wallace AM, Cochran W, Smith 